      <hedline>
        <hl1>Premature Babies: The Twins' Tale</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Nadine E Spitalnick letter calls for evaluation of risks of fertility treatments that result in multiple births (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''As the Tiniest Babies Grow, So Can Their Problems'' (front page, May 8):</p>
        <p>Studies are not only ''intensifying the long-running debate about the ethics of using sophisticated technology to save children with uncertain futures,'' but are also intensifying other ethical scenarios.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''As the Tiniest Babies Grow, So Can Their Problems'' (front page, May 8):</p>
        <p>Studies are not only ''intensifying the long-running debate about the ethics of using sophisticated technology to save children with uncertain futures,'' but are also intensifying other ethical scenarios.</p>
        <p>According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, in 1997, the pre-term rate for single infant births was 10 percent compared with 54.9 percent for twins and 93.6 percent for higher order multiples.</p>
        <p>My twin sister and I are thankful to be alive, for our combined weight at our 31-week birth hardly equaled five pounds. As medicine has much improved since our births 19 years ago, even more intense is the need to evaluate the consequences of the more widespread use of fertility-enhancing therapies that may contribute to the rise in multiple births.</p>
        <p>NADINE E. SPITALNICK  Philadelphia, May 8, 2000</p>
      </block>
